-- Isuzu to Buy Stakes in Suppliers to Help Expansion
-- Naoko Fujimura
-- 2007-05-18T08:22:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2007-05-18/isuzu-to-buy-stakes-in-suppliers-to-help-expansion-update1-.html

          
          
             Isuzu Motors Ltd. (7202) ,  Japan 's largest
maker of light-duty trucks, will spend 2.53 billion yen ($20
million) raising its stakes in two suppliers, as they seek to
raise production in line with its expansion plans.  
 The truckmaker will spend 1.54 billion yen to boost its
stake in  Jidosha Buhin Kogyo Co. (7233)  to 34.5 percent and 989.8
million yen to raise its stake in TDF Corp. to 37.13 percent, the
parts-makers said in separate statements today.  
 Isuzu needs to secure its supply of parts as it aims to
expand its production capacity and targets overseas sales. The
truckmaker plans to spend a record 60 billion yen on capital
expenditure in each of the next three years, President Yoshinori
Ida said on May 14.  
 Jidosha Buhin, a maker of industrial engines, will also
raise 897 million yen selling 1.95 million new shares to Hitachi
Construction Machinery Co. and Sumitomo Construction Machinery
Co., it said. Isuzu currently has a 27.64 percent stake in the
company.  
 TDF (5641) , based in Miyagi, northern Japan, makes forged products
used in Isuzu vehicles. The truckmaker has a 23.52 percent stake
at present.  
 The share sales will take place on June 4.  
 Isuzu expects to boost its overseas sales 4.8 percent to
389,000 vehicles in the year ending March 31, the company said on
May 14. Sales in Japan are expected fall 25 percent to 73,000
vehicles.  
 Shares of Isuzu fell 0.5 percent to 598 yen at the 3 p.m.
close on the Tokyo Stock Exchange. Jidosha Buhin shares fell 3.4
percent to 505 yen. TDF shares fell 3.3 percent to 355 yen.  
